@LoveDaniBoo If you have any questions for BEAT you can contact them at beat@cpp.edu.  @asicppbeat

@LoveDaniBoo BEAT does often partner up with different clubs and organizations to put on programs and can provide assistance through those means. If you would like programming experience, you can apply for a position in BEAT at https://t.co/lEGKPTGRmY.

@LoveDaniBoo ASI BEAT is a programming body in ASI that puts on events for students to enjoy throughout the year. Its intention is not to provide financial assistance to anyone but rather to plan and implement events.

@LoveDaniBoo CLASS students may want to schedule an appointment with David Craig, a Career Counselor, in the Career Center. David is liaison to CLASS. For additional information contact Tom Munnerlyn, director, @CPPCareerCenter .

@LoveDaniBoo Moreover, the Career Center is happy to partner with students and student groups to discuss the possibility of an entertainment Career Fair. There are a number of entertainment organizations that attend the fall and spring career fairs.

@LoveDaniBoo The Education and Non-Profit Job Fair is on Feb. 28, 2019. This event is open to all students and attracts organizations such as the City of Los Angeles and other large cities and counties in Southern California.
@LoveDaniBoo Additionally, the Career Center hosts several industry-focused fairs. While these are more targeted to certain career sectors, they are open to all students to attend.

@LoveDaniBoo The Career Center hosts 8 major career fairs each year, including the Fall All Majors Career Fair and Spring Career Fair. These events attract a wide variety of organizations. The fall 2018 Career Fair had 125 organizations and the Spring Career Fair 2018 had 235 organizations.

@LoveDaniBoo At each of these events, Music Industry Studies students were present and supported by the president. The music department and CLASS find President Coley to be an advocate for all music students and we are thrilled to have her support many of our events.

@LoveDaniBoo For her Investiture, President Coley requested that a choir be a part of the ceremony. Recently, she engaged Professor Kopplin and members of the music department (both students and faculty) at Fall Conference in presenting the sequel to ‚ÄúSemester Blues.‚Äù

@LoveDaniBoo The band loved having the president as conductor and she engaged in a meaningful dialogue with band students and Professor Badua, who leads the band. Many of the students in the band are Music Industry Studies students.

@LoveDaniBoo She regularly attends music‚Äôs events and concerts and in fact, has attended rehearsals for the Wind Ensemble and conducted the band in concert. This is an extraordinary feat for someone who is incredibly busy and, quite frankly, is not a professional musician.

@LoveDaniBoo Upon coming to CPP, President Coley revealed that she had a strong interest in music. She met many students (performance, music industry and music education students) in her first months on campus, as she was introduced to the investment made for the Steinway Initiative.

@LoveDaniBoo Regarding President Coley‚Äôs assistance to students in the Music Industry Studies program (It is not a Music Business program, but rather a Music Industry Studies program), please allow me to inform you about President Coley‚Äôs support of the music department.
